
 1. What is Kafka
 =======================================================
 -> Apache Kafka is a distributed event streaming platform used for data streaming.
 -> It follows the publish-subscribe model.
 -> Apache Kafka is a publish-subscribe based messaging system. It is fast, scalable and distributed by design.
 -> It was initially thought of as a message queue and open-source by Linkedin in 2011.
 -> Publish-subcribe to stream of records like message queue.
 -> It provide storage system, so that message can be stored asynchronously.
 -> Traditional messaging models are queue and publish-subscribe. In a queue each record goes to one consumer.
    but in publish-subscribe one message goes to multiple consumer.
    
 Props of Kafka
 =====================================================
 -> Loose coupling : Each service does not know each other regarding data update matters.
 -> Durability : Its guarantees that message will be delivered even if the consumer service is down.
                 When the consumer get up again, all message will be delivered.
 -> Scalability : Since the messages get stored in bucket, there is no need for response.
                  We create async communication between all services.
 -> Flexibility : Sender does not know who is consume the message, meaning you can add new consumer with less work.
 
 Cons of Kafka
 ====================================================
  -> The developer need to have deep knowledge about message flow .
  -> Its hard to debug.
  
